<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05009e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05009e">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05009e"> 9(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> S. Wilfrid till face touches / earth / Kevin prays in water / 50 psalms</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">He divided his time, so that in the first part of the night he recited a hundred Psalms, making at the same time two hundred genuflections; the second part he spent <mark>immersed in the water</mark> of some cold spring, keeping heart, eyes, and hands lifted up to heaven until he had finished the other <mark>fifty Psalms</mark>. &hellip; <font color="green">[252n1]</font>: Repeated prostrations and genuflections seem to have been common even in the most sublime contemplations of the saints of this period. It is related of St. Simeon Stylites, a contemporary of St. Patrick &mdash; &ldquo;He had adopted the habit of expressing his worship at times by deep reverences, bowing so low that his <mark>forehead nearly touched his feet</mark>. &hellip;&rdquo; <font color="green">[252n2]</font>: In subsequent ages, St. Patrick had many imitators of this austerity. The practice passed over into England with the Irish missioners. <mark>St. Wilfred</mark> of York probably learned it in his novitiate under the Irish monks at Lindisfarne <small> William Bullen Morris, <a name="WBML" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#WBML"><cite title="source">The Life of Saint Patrick Apostle of Ireland</cite></a>, 4th ed. (1890) 251-2</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Kevin was a 6<sup>th</sup> century Irish saint. He was very much known because of his extraordinary penitentional practices. He is the patron of Dublin. </mm> </dd></dl>
